tables.description: The audit_checks table represents a record of regular checks performed on various sites to ensure compliance and adherence to standards. It stores information about the site being checked, the date of the check, the auditor who performed the check, and the audit score obtained. This table is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify trends and patterns in compliance and risk management.

columns.description: The audit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each audit check record, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value that uniquely identifies each record in the audit_checks table. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it enables efficient data retrieval and manipulation.

The site_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the site_master table, linking each audit check record to a specific site. It stores an integer value that corresponds to the site_pk in the site_master table. This column is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand the site-level compliance and risk management.

The audit_dt column represents the date of each audit check, storing a date value that indicates when the check was performed. This column is vital in analytics and business workflows as it helps track compliance and risk management over time.

The auditor column represents the name of the person who performed each audit check, storing a character varying value that captures the auditor's name. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify trends and patterns in compliance and risk management.

The audit_score column represents the score obtained from each audit check, storing an integer value that indicates the level of compliance. This column is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify areas for improvement and track compliance over time.

tables.description: The event_log table stores a record of events that occur within the organization, including staff activities, system changes, and other notable incidents. It captures the event category, risk level, and the date of the event, providing valuable insights into the organization's operations and risk management. This table is essential in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify potential risks and areas for improvement.

columns.description: The event_pk column represents a unique identifier for each event record, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value that uniquely identifies each record in the event_log table. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it enables efficient data retrieval and manipulation.

The staff_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the staff table, linking each event record to a specific staff member. It stores an integer value that corresponds to the staff_pk in the staff table. This column is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand staff-level activities and risk management.

The event_dt column represents the date of each event, storing a date value that indicates when the event occurred. This column is vital in analytics and business workflows as it helps track events and risk management over time.

The event_category column represents the category of each event, storing a character varying value that captures the event type. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify trends and patterns in events and risk management.

The risk_level column represents the risk level associated with each event, storing an integer value that indicates the level of risk. This column is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify potential risks and areas for improvement.

tables.description: The learning_records table represents a record of courses completed by staff members, including the course name, completion date, and status. It stores information about the staff member who completed the course, their unit, and the date of completion. This table is vital in analytics and business workflows as it helps track staff development and training needs.

It stores an integer value that uniquely identifies each record in the learning_records table. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it enables efficient data retrieval and manipulation.

The staff_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the staff table, linking each learning record to a specific staff member. It stores an integer value that corresponds to the staff_pk in the staff table. This column is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand staff-level training and development.

The course_name column represents the name of each course completed by staff members, storing a character varying value that captures the course title. This column is vital in analytics and business workflows as it helps track staff development and training needs.

The course_dt column represents the date of each course completion, storing a date value that indicates when the course was completed. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it helps track staff development and training over time.

The completion_status column represents the status of each course completion, storing a character varying value that captures the completion status. This column is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify trends and patterns in staff development and training.

tables.description: The org_units table represents a record of organizational units within the organization, including their titles, site affiliations, and unit heads. It stores information about the unit's creation date and other relevant details. This table is essential in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand the organization's structure and hierarchy.

columns.description: The unit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each organizational unit, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value that uniquely identifies each record in the org_units table. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it enables efficient data retrieval and manipulation.

The unit_title column represents the title of each organizational unit, storing a character varying value that captures the unit title. This column is vital in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand the organization's structure and hierarchy.

The site_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the site_master table, linking each organizational unit to a specific site. It stores an integer value that corresponds to the site_pk in the site_master table. This column is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand the site-level organizational structure.

The unit_head column represents the head of each organizational unit, storing a character varying value that captures the unit head's name. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify trends and patterns in organizational structure and leadership.

The created_on column represents the date of creation for each organizational unit, storing a timestamp value that indicates when the unit was created. This column is vital in analytics and business workflows as it helps track changes in organizational structure over time.

tables.description: The site_master table represents a record of sites operated by the organization, including their titles, nations, and regions. It stores information about the site's creation date and other relevant details. This table is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand the organization's geographical presence and operations.

This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it enables efficient data retrieval and manipulation.

The nation column represents the nation associated with each site, storing a character varying value that captures the nation name. This column is crucial in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand the organization's global presence and operations.

tables.description: The staff table represents a record of staff members within the organization, including their full names, unit affiliations, roles, and joining dates. It stores information about the staff member's details and other relevant data. This table is vital in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand the organization's human resources and talent management.

columns.description: The staff_pk column represents a unique identifier for each staff member, serving as a primary key. It stores an integer value that uniquely identifies each record in the staff table. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it enables efficient data retrieval and manipulation.

The staff_fullname column represents the full name of each staff member, storing a character varying value that captures the staff member's full name. This column is vital in analytics and business workflows as it helps understand the organization's human resources and talent management.

The unit_fk column represents the foreign key referencing the org_units table, linking each staff member to a specific organizational unit. It stores an integer value that corresponds to the unit_pk in the org_units table. The role_name column represents the role of each staff member, storing a character varying value that captures the staff member's role. This column is essential in analytics and business workflows as it helps identify trends and patterns in staff roles and responsibilities.
